div.p:
The means and methods which God makes uſe of, in calling forth his miniſters, are exceeding various; ſo that no exact ſteps can be deſcribed by us, for his calling forth his miniſters, any more than for his calling ſouls into the kingdom of his grace. But the teaching of the Spirit of God in his word, a view of the worth of ſouls and of the preſent ſtate of things among the people, with the command of Chriſt to preach his goſpel to them, is the eſſence of an internal call into that great work. The external call is by his church, who are inveſted with authority from Chriſt to carry all his laws into execution in his name. For, after warning believers of the danger, of being ſpoiled through philoſophy and vain deceit, by men who do not hold THE HEAD, he ſays, Let the word of Chriſt dwell in you richly in all wiſdom; teaching and admoniſhing one another in pſalms, and hymns, and ſpiritual ſongs, ſinging with grace in your hearts to the Lord. And whatſoever ye do in word or deed, do all in the name of the Lord Jeſus, giving thanks to God and the Father by him. Col. ii. 8—10, 18—23. iii. 16, 17. In the laſt of theſe chapters he ſays, Covetouſneſs is idolatry. And in another place he ſays, No whoremonger, nor unclean perſon, nor covetous man who is an idolater, hath any inheritance in the kingdom of Chriſt, and of God. Eph. v. 5. And ſuch have ever had a great influence in all national churches, by whom all wars have been managed. But when the houſe of God, which is his church, ſhall be eſtabliſhed upon his revealed will, above all the powers of this

world, bloody wars will come to an end. And believers will ſay, All people will walk every one in the name of his god, and we will walk in the name of the Lord our God forever and ever. Micah iv. 1—5. The ſaints of the Moſt High ſhall take the kingdom, and poſſeſs the kingdom forever, even forever and ever. Dan. vii. 18. For, though the devil will deceive multitudes, after the reign of the ſaints for a thouſand years, yet their complete deſtruction will prevent any interruption of the kingdom of the ſaints. Rev. xx. 7—9. All men deſire ſafety and happineſs, and no men would diſobey the revealed will of God, if they were not deceived. Titus iii. 3. Evil men and ſeducers ſhall wax worſe and worſe, deceiving, and being deceived. 2 Tim. iii. 13. No men would deceive others, if they were not firſt deceived themſelves. And Chriſt ſays, If it were poſſible, they ſhall deceive the very elect. Mat. xxiv. 24. And multitudes are now ſo much deceived, as to deny that God has an elect number among mankind, diſtinct from the reſt. But the apoſtle Peter writes to the ſaints, and calls them the Elect according to the foreknowledge of God the Father, through ſanctification of the Spirit unto obedience, and ſprinkling of the blood of Ieſus Chriſt. And to them he ſays, The elders which are among you I exhort, who am alſo an elder, and a witneſs of the ſufferings of Chriſt, and alſo a partaker of the glory that ſhall be revealed; feed the flock of God which is among you, taking the overſight thereof, not by conſtraint, but willingly; not for filthy lucre, but of a ready mind; neither as being lords over God's heritage, but being enſamples of the flock. And when the chief Shepherd ſhall appear, ye ſhall receive a crown of glory that fadeth not away. Likewiſe ye younger, ſubmit yourſelves unto the elder;

yea, all of you be ſubject one to and be clothed with humility: for God reſiſteth the proud, and giveth grace unto the humble. 1 Peter i. 2. v. 1—5.
